st one confirmed case in an American national increases transmission risk\n- **Uganda involvement**: More developed infrastructure and international connectivity than DRC alone\n- **Incubation period**: 2-21 day window allows undetected travel\n\n#### (f) Community Prediction Comparison\nNo community prediction data available to compare against.\n\n---\n\n#### Rationale\n\nThe critical insight is that **historical precedent strongly favors containment**. The two previous Bundibugyo outbreaks (2007, 2012) occurred in similar geographic regions with similar epidemiological conditions, yet produced zero cases outside Africa. This is the strongest baseline.\n\nHowever, this case differs from those outbreaks in important ways:\n- Larger current case count (246 suspected vs. smaller historical outbreaks)\n- Presence of American nationals in the affected region\n- The 2014-2016 Zaire epidemic demonstrated that Ebola *can* reach US soil (4 cases)\n\nThe 7-month timeframe is relatively short. Entry restrictions are already in place. The lack of vaccines/therapeutics actually reduces likelihood of asymptomatic spread.\n\nWeighing these factors:\n- Base rate from BVD history: ~2-5% (two outbreaks, zero US cases)\n- Adjustment for larger outbreak scale: +2-3%\n- Adjustment for active containment measures: -1-2%\n- Adjustment for short remaining timeframe: -1%\n\n**Final estimate: 4-6%**\n\nThe status quo (no US cases) is heavily favored by historical precedent, but the current outbreak's larger scale and the precedent from Zaire Ebola prevent this from being negligible.\n\n**Probability: 5%**\n\n\n## R1: Forecaster 2 Reasoning\n### Forecasting Analysis: Bundibugyo Ebola in the US Before 2027\n\n#### (a) Time Left Until Outcome is Known\nApproximately **7 months** (from May 27, 2026 to January 1, 2027)\n\n#### (b) Status Quo Outcome if Nothing Changed\n**No confirmed cases in the US.** The outbreak remains geographically contained to DRC and Uganda, with travel restrictions limiting entry from affected regions. This is the baseline expectation given historical precedent.\n\n#### (c) Scenario Resulting in \"No\" Outcome\nThe outbreak is controlled through public health interventions in Uganda and DRC over the next 6-7 months. Travel restrictions remain in place and are effective. No infected individuals reach the US before January 1, 2027. This aligns with the pattern of the two previous BVD outbreaks (2007, 2012), which remained geographically contained to Africa.\n\n#### (d) Scenario Resulting in \"Yes\" Outcome\nAn infected individual (likely a healthcare worker, researcher, or family member of a confirmed case) travels to the US during the incubation period (2-21 days) before symptom onset. They are diagnosed in a US facility before January 1, 2027. Alternatively, a US citizen working in the affected region becomes infected and is diagnosed upon return to the US.\n\n#### (e) Key Factors Influencing This Forecast\n\n**Factors supporting lower probability:**\n- **Historical precedent**: Two previous BVD outbreaks (2007, 2012) produced zero cases outside Africa\n- **Active travel restrictions**: US authorities have already invoked public health law to limit entry from affected regions\n- **Short timeframe**: Only 7 months remain; outbreak control efforts may suppress transmission\n- **Status quo bias**: Most outbreaks remain geographically contained; international spread is the exception, not the rule\n- **No licensed therapeutics**: This may actually reduce travel incentives for treatment-seeking in the US\n\n**Factors supporting higher probability:**\n- **Current PHEIC status**: Elevated alert level increases monitoring and awareness\n- **American nationals present**: At least one American has tested positive in DRC, indicating US presence in the region\n- **Zaire precedent**: The 2014-2016 Zaire epidemic produced 4 US cases and multiple medical evacuations, showing international spread is possible\n- **Healthcare worker risk**: US medical personnel may be deployed to assist with outbreak response\n- **7-month window**: Sufficient time for outbreak evolution and potential international spread\n\n#### (f) Community Prediction Divergence\nNo community prediction data is available for comparison.\n\n---\n\n#### Rationale\n\nThe critical insight is that **status quo outcomes dominate forecasting**. The two previous BVD outbreaks produced zero international cases despite occurring in the same regions. This is the strongest historical anchor.\n\nHowever, the 2014-2016 Zaire epidemic demonstrates that Ebola *can* reach the US (4 cases confirmed), though this required a much larger outbreak (>11,000 cases). The current BVD outbreak is smaller and already subject to travel restrictions.\n\nThe presence of American nationals in the affected region and the PHEIC declaration increase risk above the baseline of previous BVD outbreaks, but travel restrictions and the short 7-month timeframe work against international spread.\n\nWeighing these factors:\n- Base rate from BVD history: ~2-3% (zero cases in two previous outbreaks)\n- Adjustment upward for American presence and PHEIC: +3-4%\n- Adjustment downward for active travel restrictions: -1-2%\n\n**Final estimate: 4-6%**\n\nProbability: **5%**\n\n\n## R2: Forecaster 1 Reasoning\n### Forecast Analysis: Bundibugyo Ebola in the US Before 2027\n\n#### (a) Time Left Until Outcome is Known\nApproximately **7 months** (from May 27, 2026 to January 1, 2027)\n\n#### (b) Status Quo Outcome if Nothing Changed\n**No confirmed cases in the US.** The outbreak remains geographically contained to DRC and Uganda, with travel restrictions limiting entry from affected regions. No cases spread to US soil.\n\n#### (c) Scenario Resulting in \"No\" Outcome\nThe outbreak is contained through public health interventions in Uganda and DRC. Travel restrictions remain effective. The American national who tested positive in the DRC either recovers or dies there without traveling to the US. The outbreak follows the pattern of previous BVD outbreaks (2007, 2012), which remained geographically isolated to Africa. No secondary transmission chains establish themselves in the US.\n\n#### (d) Scenario Resulting in \"Yes\" Outcome\nAn infected individual (either asymptomatic or in early symptomatic stages) travels from the affected region to the US before detection. They develop symptoms and are tested in a US facility, resulting in the first laboratory-confirmed BVD case on US soil. Alternatively, a healthcare worker treating patients in DRC/Uganda becomes infected and travels to the US before diagnosis.\n\n#### (e) Key Factors Influencing This Forecast\n\n**Factors Supporting Lower Probability:**\n- **Historical precedent**: Previous BVD outbreaks (2007, 2012) did not produce cases outside Africa despite similar circumstances\n- **Active containment**: US has invoked travel restrictions and public health measures\n- **Short timeframe**: Only 7 months remain; outbreak must spread internationally quickly\n- **Status quo bias**: Most outbreaks remain geographically contained; international spread is the exception\n- **No specific therapeutics**: While concerning for severity, this doesn't necessarily increase transmission probability\n\n**Factors Supporting Higher Probability:**\n- **Confirmed international spread already**: Cases already in Uganda (outside DRC epicenter) suggest some transmission capability\n- **American nationals present**: At least one American tested positive in DRC, indicating US citizen exposure\n- **2014-2016 precedent**: Zaire ebolavirus did produce 4 US cases during West African epidemic, showing international spread is possible\n- **Lack of vaccines/therapeutics**: May increase severity and hospitalization needs, potentially increasing detection\n- **Modern travel**: International connectivity makes transmission possible\n\n#### (f) Community Prediction Comparison\nNo community prediction data available to compare against.\n\n---\n\n#### Rationale\n\nThe critical question is whether Bundibugyo virus will deviate from its historical pattern. The two previous BVD outbreaks remained geographically isolated despite occurring in regions with international connectivity. This suggests either:\n1. The virus has lower transmissibility than other Ebola species\n2. Containment measures are effective\n3. Geographic/epidemiological factors limit spread\n\nHowever, the 2014-2016 Zaire epidemic demonstrates that Ebola *can* reach the US, and we already have confirmed international spread (Uganda cases) and American nationals in the affected zone.\n\nThe 7-month timeframe is relatively short for an outbreak to establish itself internationally and produce a US case. The combination of:\n- Active travel restrictions\n- Historical containment of BVD\n- Short remaining timeframe\n- Status quo bias (most outbreaks don't reach the US)\n\n...suggests a relatively low probability, but not negligible given the precedent of the 2014-2016 epidemic and existing international cases.\n\n**Probability: 12%**\n\n\n## R2: Forecaster 2 Reasoning\n### Bundibugyo Ebola Case in US Before 2027 - Forecast Analysis\n\n#### (a) Time Left Until Outcome is Known\nApproximately **7 months** (from May 27, 2026 to January 1, 2027)\n\n#### (b) Status Quo Outcome if Nothing Changed\nThe status quo strongly favors **No**. The US has already implemented entry restrictions from affected regions. Historical precedent shows that while Zaire ebolavirus reached the US during the 2014-2016 epidemic (4 cases), these were primarily healthcare workers with known exposure who were medically evacuated. Bundibugyo virus has never previously spread outside Africa despite two prior outbreaks. The current outbreak is in remote areas of DRC and Uganda with limited direct travel connections to the US.\n\n#### (c) Scenario Resulting in No Outcome\nAn infected individual from the affected region either:\n- Does not travel to the US before symptom onset\n- Is ca